about the whole thing,

00:44:58.290 --> 00:45:02.400
not realizing that he was
coming off as a complete racist.

00:45:02.400 --> 00:45:03.860
And so I think
people don't always

00:45:03.860 --> 00:45:06.740
realize how the
thoughts in their head

00:45:06.740 --> 00:45:08.470
sound when they come
out of their mouth.

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:17.450
And I talked to a woman once
who tried to convince me

00:45:17.450 --> 00:45:21.250
that one in five
Muslims was a terrorist.

00:45:21.250 --> 00:45:23.530
And then she said, do the math.

00:45:23.530 --> 00:45:25.750
And so I did.

00:45:25.750 --> 00:45:30.129
And it would make about
500 million terrorists.

00:45:30.129 --> 00:45:31.670
And I thought to
myself, why the fuck

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:32.930
has it taken us so long then?

00:45:32.930 --> 00:45:37.720
If we have that many
people working for us?

00:45:37.720 --> 00:45:39.090
Jesus, we are the worst!

00:45:42.800 --> 00:45:45.040
But things like that.

00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:49.060
And then she was amazed
that she was getting threats

00:45:49.060 --> 00:45:50.760
from people when
that piece aired.

00:45:50.760 --> 00:45:53.245
And not from Muslims, from
like liberal white people who

00:45:53.245 --> 00:45:54.550
were like, you can't say that.

00:45:54.550 --> 00:45:55.700
That's just not true.

00:45:55.700 --> 00:45:58.450
So I think people just
don't realize sometimes.

00:45:58.450 --> 00:46:00.080
Yeah?

00:46:00.080 --> 00:46:00.950
How the work?

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:09.350
Well, I think theater is a great
grounding, base level education

00:46:09.350 --> 00:46:13.350
in terms of acting
and [INAUDIBLE] now.

00:46:13.350 --> 00:46:18.230
Even in "The Daily Show."

00:46:18.230 --> 00:46:22.062
For example, people always
think, oh, Aasif Mandvi--

00:46:22.062 --> 00:46:23.770
you're just yourself
on "The Daily Show."

00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:26.720
But I'm actually not myself.

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:29.830
I consider myself
playing a character who

00:46:29.830 --> 00:46:33.430
happens to have my
name, and a whole team

00:46:33.430 --> 00:46:38.407
of Jewish writers who can
travel with him wherever he goes

00:46:38.407 --> 00:46:40.240
and a greenscreen that
he walks around with.

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:45.160
But the thing is that it
was a great education.

00:46:45.160 --> 00:46:47.950
Theater was a great
place to start.

00:46:47.950 --> 00:46:51.810
Because if you
can do theater, it

00:46:51.810 --> 00:46:56.584
teaches you everything about how
to be on television and film.

00:46:56.584 --> 00:46:58.000
You can't always
do the other way.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.810
You see film actors or TV
actors trying to do theater,

00:47:00.810 --> 00:47:02.510
and they fail.

00:47:02.510 --> 00:47:07.400
But from theater to
television, I think often,

00:47:07.400 --> 00:47:10.410
it gives you the tools.

00:47:10.410 --> 00:47:15.420
And playwriting, just in
terms of how a scene can work,

00:47:15.420 --> 00:47:16.125
and what makes.

00:47:16.125 --> 00:47:16.750
And it's great.

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:19.870
Because on the brink, I'm
actually a co-producer

00:47:19.870 --> 00:47:21.860
and a writer on
the show, as well.

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:24.390
And so it's been
really great to be

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:30.510
able to work with those
writers on a TV show.

00:47:30.510 --> 00:47:33.580
And a lot of those guys
are playwrights as well,

00:47:33.580 --> 00:47:36.930
who have transitioned
into television writing.

00:47:36.930 --> 00:47:39.200
In fact, a lot of the
great television writers

00:47:39.200 --> 00:47:42.180
today started as playwrights.

00:47:42.180 --> 00:47:44.240
Lewis Black started
as a playwright.

00:47:44.240 --> 00:47:45.800
Not a lot of you knew that.

00:47:45.800 --> 00:47:46.770
That's one to grow on.

00:47:46.770 --> 00:47:49.850
There you go.

