treated equally like others.

00:49:42.730 --> 00:49:46.330
Did you feel like you
became equal at some point?

00:49:46.330 --> 00:49:50.477
Or did you have to come to
America for you to feel equal?

00:49:50.477 --> 00:49:52.060
AASIF MANDVI: Did I
feel like I became

00:49:52.060 --> 00:49:53.290
equal when I got to America?

00:49:53.290 --> 00:49:55.290
You haven't been in America
very long, have you?

00:50:00.630 --> 00:50:04.470
Look-- from my perspective,
there is much more

00:50:04.470 --> 00:50:07.520
representation of South
Asians in the media,

00:50:07.520 --> 00:50:12.480
and on television, and
in general out there.

00:50:12.480 --> 00:50:14.750
Do we still have a long
way to go in terms of that?

00:50:14.750 --> 00:50:15.640
Yeah.

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:17.730
Look, at the end of the
day, Hollywood still

00:50:17.730 --> 00:50:19.780
prefers white people.

00:50:19.780 --> 00:50:21.750
They're easier to
light, apparently.

00:50:28.650 --> 00:50:31.730
You don't need all
those gobos and things.

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:39.990
But look, we are a technological
milestone in the history,

00:50:39.990 --> 00:50:41.830
and this place is
full of Indian people.

00:50:41.830 --> 00:50:45.130
So I consider that a
little bit of a victory.

00:50:45.130 --> 00:50:46.906
AUDIENCE: I don't
mean as a group.

00:50:46.906 --> 00:50:48.530
AASIF MANDVI: Right,
you mean personal.

00:50:48.530 --> 00:50:49.457
AUDIENCE: I mean you.

00:50:49.457 --> 00:50:50.790
AASIF MANDVI: Here's what I did.

00:50:50.790 --> 00:50:56.360
I got on TV, and then that
is the great equalizer

00:50:56.360 --> 00:50:59.940
in terms of having a platform
to be able to say things.

00:50:59.940 --> 00:51:04.763
Even the fact that you guys are
listening to me talk right now.

00:51:04.763 --> 00:51:09.270
But in a larger
cultural context,

00:51:09.270 --> 00:51:14.720
do I still deal with racism,
