AASIF MANDVI: Right there.

00:53:15.674 --> 00:53:17.714
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
what your thoughts were

00:53:17.714 --> 00:53:18.990
on colorblind casting.

00:53:18.990 --> 00:53:21.130
I know that "Grey's Anatomy's"
a show that they've mentioned.

00:53:21.130 --> 00:53:22.350
It's a thing I was
wondering if you

00:53:22.350 --> 00:53:23.610
think it's the
future of casting.

00:53:23.610 --> 00:53:24.985
AASIF MANDVI:
Colorblind casting?

00:53:24.985 --> 00:53:29.824
Like you mean anybody, any
ethnicity can play any role?

00:53:29.824 --> 00:53:31.240
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
so they don't have

00:53:31.240 --> 00:53:35.010
a typical look
for the character.

00:53:35.010 --> 00:53:38.859
AASIF MANDVI: Listen, that is, I
think, the tapestry of America.

00:53:38.859 --> 00:53:40.650
I don't think we're
going to get to a place

00:53:40.650 --> 00:53:48.265
where we will have-- unless,
maybe they could probably

00:53:48.265 --> 00:53:49.390
do it if they were adopted.

00:53:49.390 --> 00:53:51.540
I was going to say, brown
parents with white kids.

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:54.400
But you could do that
in a certain scenario.

00:53:54.400 --> 00:53:58.620
But I think in terms of,
there are roles out there

00:53:58.620 --> 00:54:01.040
that anybody can
play, in terms of,

00:54:01.040 --> 00:54:02.770
it doesn't matter what
ethnicity you are?

00:54:02.770 --> 00:54:04.980
I don't think we are there yet.

00:54:04.980 --> 00:54:08.720
But there are still more
roles for white people

00:54:08.720 --> 00:54:10.600
than anybody else.

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:16.964
And there's always that one
role for the brown person.

00:54:16.964 --> 00:54:19.005
I was just having this
conversation earlier today

00:54:19.005 --> 00:54:20.750
with someone where
it was like, there's

00:54:20.750 --> 00:54:26.260
one role for a brown person
and 50 roles for white people.

00:54:26.260 --> 00:54:27.510
So that still exists.

00:54:27.510 --> 00:54:28.860
And hopefully, that will change.

00:54:28.860 --> 00:54:32.570
And Shonda Rhimes is
someone who is actually

00:54:32.570 --> 00:54:34.950
pushing the boundaries of
that, pushing the envelope.

00:54:34.950 --> 00:54:36.325
And this is why
I've always said,

00:54:36.325 --> 00:54:40.350
we need more ethnic, or at
least minority immigrant,

00:54:40.350 --> 00:54:45.240
whatever you want to call it--
writers, producers, creators

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:48.970
out there, and people who are
shaping the culture in the way

00:54:48.970 --> 00:54:51.260
that Google is.

00:54:51.260 --> 00:54:53.720
Because ultimately, those
things get reflected back

00:54:53.720 --> 00:54:58.705
into the media and into the
larger society as a whole.

00:54:58.705 --> 00:55:00.080
Let's face it;
one of the reasons

00:55:00.080 --> 00:55:03.420
I was cast in "The Internship"
as the head of the Google

00:55:03.420 --> 00:55:05.560
intern program, and
I'm South Asian,

00:55:05.560 --> 00:55:10.680
is because you guys
are here at Google.

00:55:10.680 --> 00:55:15.090
And so that representation
needs to be shown.

00:55:15.090 --> 00:55:19.037
If that movie had been
made 20 years ago,

00:55:19.037 --> 00:55:20.370
there would have been no Google.

00:55:20.370 --> 00:55:23.650
But if it was a
movie like that, it

00:55:23.650 --> 00:55:25.860
would've been a white
guy in that role playing

00:55:25.860 --> 00:55:27.550
the boss, as it were.

00:55:27.550 --> 00:55:31.910
So I think that, for me,
personally, was something

00:55:31.910 --> 00:55:34.560
that I benefited from
in terms of the larger

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:38.244
cultural visibility.

